occurrenceRemarks: Locally occasional.; 40 cm tall, brown fruit, small green leaves, dark brown reddish stem towards base, pubescent stem and leaves, perennial.

habitat: Grassy one or two acre roadside slope, east-facing. Ankle-height plants that are sometimes mowed, mostly open except for a few trees near train tracks. Single-stemmed herb, roughly 1 ft. high. Stem: gray-green with small reddish brown thorns, thorns single or in pairs (no clusters), thicker toward the base. Leaves: slightly greener than stem, paler underside. Flowers: medium purple, five petals joined at base and pointing downward, each with one purple vein running from the point to the center, vein is yellow in center. 5 headless yellow anthers. Buds: yellow-gray and half covered with bracts. Fruits: probably underripe when we saw them. Yellow-green with dark green stripes that do not meet at the bottom.
locality: Northeast corner of Nichols St. and East Third St. Grassy one or two acre roadside slope, east-facing, surrounded by two roads, a railroad and a building. 32° 34' 32.66N 97° 19' 23.55W
